meta:
  origin:
    producer: World Bank
    title: World Development Indicators
    description: |-
      The World Development Indicators (WDI) is the World Bank's primary collection of development indicators, compiled from officially recognized international sources. It presents the most current and accurate global development data available, covering topics such as agriculture, economy, education, health, and environment.

      The land under cereal production indicator refers to harvested area, although some countries report only sown or cultivated area. Cereals include wheat, rice, maize, barley, oats, rye, millet, sorghum, buckwheat, and mixed grains. Production data on cereals relate to crops harvested for dry grain only. Cereal crops harvested for hay or harvested green for food, feed, or silage and those used for grazing are excluded. Data is originally sourced from the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO).
    title_snapshot: World Development Indicators - Land under cereal production
    description_snapshot: This snapshot contains data on land under cereal production (hectares) drawn from the World Bank's World Development Indicators. An index was derived by Our World in Data, setting 1961 as the base year (1961 = 100). World/global figures prior to 1991 have been adjusted to account for the Former Soviet Union (USSR), whose land area was not included in the original World Bank dataset.
    citation_full: 'World Bank. World Development Indicators. Available at: http://data.worldbank.org/data-catalog/world-development-indicators (2017).'
    url_main: http://data.worldbank.org/data-catalog/world-development-indicators
    date_accessed: '2017-07-18'
    date_published: '2017'
